name: nonylcyclohexane
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: The nonylcyclohexane molecule can be thought of as a cyclohexane ring with a nonyl (9-carbon) subgroup attached. The melting point of such a compound would be influenced predominantly by the size and shape of the molecule and the resulting intermolecular forces. Compared to simple cyclohexane, which has a melting point of 6.5°C, the nonyl group significantly increases the molecular weight and hydrocarbon chain interactions, which could increase the melting point. However, as nonylcyclohexane has a long nonpolar alkyl chain which can inhibit packing efficiency due to increased chain entanglement and reduced symmetry, this can lower the melting point compared to smaller, more symmetrical alkylcyclohexanes. Since cyclohexane has a melting point of 6.5°C and considering a long nonyl group could raise the melting point by approximately 20 units due to increased van der Waals forces but lower it by approximately 36.5 units due to decreased packing efficiency (taking into account that a similar long alkane like n-nonane has a melting point of around –51°C), the overall effect is a predicted decrease in melting point from cyclohexane.
